<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-761-940  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 761 940.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  August 1990 v19 n10 p45(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Trouble in the cards: Madge points the finger at 802.5 spec.andO;(Madge Networks Inc. claims the IEEE 802.5 token ring standard isflawed) (includes a related article on jitter, the curse of asynchronous LAN)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, Johna Till.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Madge Networks Inc claims a flaw in the IEEE 802.5 token ringstandard has caused a problem with its 16M-bps token ring adaptercards, causing the 802.5 committee to set up a task force to findout whether or not the specification is flawed.andP;  The company'scards will not work in networks with more than about 20 nodes,according to a Madge spokesman, but the claim of a specificationflaw has been met with skepticism, in part because similar boardsfrom IBM, Proteon and other vendors have not experienced similarproblems.andP;  The Madge boards are based on Texas Instruments' tokenring interface chips, as are most other such 16M-bps token ringboards; the problems have been traced to a preproduction versionof a new chip, code-named Falcon, but Madge blames thespecification rather than the chip.andP;  Texas Instruments and Madgetested the Falcon chip and board extensively, causing it toconclude that the 802.5 standard is not adequate, according toMadge; TI denies finding fault with the standard.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Madge Networks Inc. (product recall).andO;Topic:     Token Ring NetworksStandardsCommunications Boards-CardsProduct FailuresProduct RecallSpecificationsManufacturersCompatible Hardware.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>